<h2 class="page">Russian letters denoting <br>consonant sounds</h2>

<h3 class="page-path">
	<span class="int-links">
	<a href="russian-reading.html">Reading in Russian</a>
	<span class="int-arrow">--&gt;</span> 
	<a href="/russian-reading-alphabet.html">Learn Russian alphabet</a>

	<span class="int-arrow">--&gt;</span> Lesson 2
	</span>
</h3>

<p>
In this lesson, you can work with 10 Russian letters denoting consonant sounds. 
These letters may look similar for English speaking people, but most of them sounds quite differently from English letters.
</p>
<p>
Russian letters <span class="letter">К</span>, <span class="letter">М</span>, and <span class="letter">Т</span> look and sound very similarly as compared to respective English letters. 
The Russian letter <span class="letter">С</span> look and sound like the English <span class="letter">C</span>, but it never denotes the sound [k].
Letters <span class="letter">В</span>, <span class="letter">Н</span>, <span class="letter">Р</span>, <span class="letter">Х</span> look like English letters, but they denote quite different sounds. Letters <span class="letter">З</span> and <span class="letter">Ч</span> have common traits with numbers 3 and 4, respectively.
As a rule, the <a href="/basic-letters.html#basic">basic meaning</a> of a consonant letter is the consonant sound which forms the name of this letter. 
</p>

